newsitem.title: ARGENTINA: Argentine bonds fall, fail to break resistance.
newsitem.headline: Argentine bonds fall, fail to break resistance.

text.p: Argentine bonds fell Tuesday as the market failed to break through resistance after three days of gains.
The market rose early in the session, but "there were no genuine flows," to back up the gains so prices turned lower on light profit-taking, said a trader.
Argentina's FRB due 2005 fell 3/4 to 83-1/4, while the local dollar-denominated Bocon Previsional 2 due 2001 fell $0.40 to 119.60.
The trader said the FRB was unable to break through resistance at 84.
An analyst at a large foreign bank said "it is still a traders market," adding that it is "waiting for something to happen" before making another upward push.
Traders continued to say the market suffered from low volumes, something that has plagued it for the last two weeks.
In the money markets, call money rates were unchanged at 6.85 percent.
